SECTION 9: CONCLUSIONS AND NEXT STEPS

9.1 What We Deliver
Our pipeline delivers a complete mission intelligence package for the lunar south polar ice detection problem. This includes an ice probability map with confidence levels from 0 to 1 derived from DFSAR radar analysis; a terrain hazard map derived from OHRC optical morphology analysis; a ranked list of the top three candidate landing sites with full safety metrics; an optimized rover traverse route from landing site to ice target with solar-power feasibility assessment; and resource estimates in three scenarios covering ice volume, mass, water yield, and habitat support duration.
Every output carries explicit authorship (prototype output — our processing), data provenance (generated from Chandrayaan-2 data), method description (the specific algorithm and parameters used), and honesty qualifications (what the output claims and what it does not claim). This combination of scientific rigor, honest uncertainty, and mission-level completeness represents our core contribution to the Bharatiya Antariksh Hackathon 2026.

9.2 Build Phase Deliverables
Several capabilities are correctly identified as build-phase deliverables requiring resources beyond the hackathon window. True slope mapping requires LOLA DEM integration or stereo photoclinometry from overlapping OHRC frames. Calibrated CPR and DOP require the full polarimetric DFSAR data product rather than the browse image proxy. Ground truth validation requires comparison with published CPR maps from Hayne et al. and Bhatt et al. Multi-epoch illumination modeling for definitive PSR boundary mapping requires ray-tracing over a full lunar year. These build-phase items are acknowledged explicitly in our outputs rather than silently omitted, which is both scientifically honest and demonstrates that we understand the full scope of the problem.

9.3 Final Statement
The lunar south pole holds the key to sustainable human presence beyond Earth. Water ice, if present in the quantities our analysis suggests, could support long-duration human habitation, generate rocket propellant for return missions, and serve as the foundation of a permanent lunar outpost. Detecting, locating, and characterizing this resource is among the most important scientific and engineering challenges of our generation.
Voyagers of Shadows has built a pipeline that takes raw Chandrayaan-2 data and produces the intelligence needed to answer the fundamental mission questions: where to land, how to get to the ice, and what it means for human presence on the Moon. We are ready to execute this pipeline in the 30-hour hackathon window and deliver results that are scientifically honest, technically rigorous, and directly actionable for ISRO mission planning.

